## Below, we start the SNP calling. We use "screen" to run in on a screen for 72 h, see https://linuxize.com/post/how-to-use-linux-screen/?utm_content=cmp-true

## We  need to calculate the "--skip-coverage"
## --skip-coverage = total DP combined across all samples; assuming max 400x per sample per region, 400X per sample * 385 samples = 154,000
## However, with "--limit-coverage 100", the effective max total DP is actually 100 × 385 = 38,500, so --skip-coverage 57750 will almost never trigger in practice. If --limit-coverage 100 is, a more meaningful value would be: 100×385×1.5 ≈ 57,750!
## The 1.5× buffer accounts for any sampling variance. 
## This will be set in the freebayes code below.
## An additional note on "--skip-coverage": a value of, e.g., "200" means that each region will be skipped that has a higher sum count of 200. You can also reduced this value by using this idea for --skip-coverage: "Number of samples" x "mean coverage across all samples" x 2
## We also need a folder "raw" under the bam_final folder
## To detach from the "screen", use "Ctrl + A, then D". To list screen sessions, use "screen -ls". To reattach, use "screen -r"

